    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Learned Positional Embeddings Are"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Instead of computing position vectors from a formula, learned positional embeddings store one trainable vector per position in a lookup table. The table is an "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "nn.Embedding(max_len, d_model)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — identical in structure to the token embedding table, but indexed by position (0, 1, 2, …) rather than vocabulary id. These vectors are initialised randomly and updated by gradient descent alongside all other model parameters."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Learned positional embedding lookup table showing position indices 0-511 mapped to d_model-dimensional learned vectors, and a comparison table against sinusoidal encodings"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport math\n\nclass LearnedPositionalEmbedding(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, max_len: int, d_model: int, dropout: float = 0.1):\n        super().__init__()\n        # One learned vector per position — shape (max_len, d_model)\n        self.pos_emb = nn.Embedding(max_len, d_model)\n        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(dropout)\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        \"\"\"\n        x: (batch, seq_len) — token ids\n        \"\"\"\n        batch, seq_len = x.shape\n        # Create position indices [0, 1, 2, ..., seq_len-1]\n        positions = torch.arange(seq_len, device=x.device)  # (seq_len,)\n        pos_vectors = self.pos_emb(positions)                # (seq_len, d_model)\n        # pos_vectors broadcasts over the batch dimension\n        return self.dropout(pos_vectors)                     # added to token embedding externally\n\n\nclass TransformerEmbedding(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, vocab_size: int, d_model: int, max_len: int = 512,\n                 dropout: float = 0.1):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.token_emb = nn.Embedding(vocab_size, d_model)\n        self.pos_emb   = nn.Embedding(max_len, d_model)\n        self.dropout   = nn.Dropout(dropout)\n        self.scale     = math.sqrt(d_model)\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        batch, seq_len = x.shape\n        positions = torch.arange(seq_len, device=x.device)\n        token_vecs = self.token_emb(x) * self.scale   # (batch, seq_len, d_model)\n        pos_vecs   = self.pos_emb(positions)           # (seq_len, d_model) → broadcasts\n        return self.dropout(token_vecs + pos_vecs)\n\n# Check parameter count\nmodel = TransformerEmbedding(vocab_size=30522, d_model=768, max_len=512)\npos_params = sum(p.numel() for p in model.pos_emb.parameters())\nprint(f\"Positional embedding params: {pos_params:,}\")  # 393,216"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BERT's Implementation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BERT uses learned positional embeddings with max_len = 512. Its total input embedding is the sum of three embedding tables: token embeddings, position embeddings, and segment (sentence A/B) embeddings:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import BertModel, BertTokenizer\nimport torch\n\ntokenizer = BertTokenizer.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')\nmodel = BertModel.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')\n\n# Inspect BERT's position embeddings\npos_emb = model.embeddings.position_embeddings\nprint(pos_emb)          # Embedding(512, 768)\nprint(pos_emb.weight.shape)  # torch.Size([512, 768])\n\n# These are learned — they change during fine-tuning\nprint(pos_emb.weight.requires_grad)  # True\n\n# What BERT's embedding layer does (simplified):\n# input = token_emb + position_emb + segment_emb\n# All three are added; result is layer-normed and dropped out\ntext = \"Hello world\"\ninputs = tokenizer(text, return_tensors='pt')\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    outputs = model(**inputs, output_hidden_states=True)\nprint(outputs.last_hidden_state.shape)  # (1, 4, 768) — 2 tokens + [CLS] + [SEP]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Advantages of Learned Embeddings"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Task-adaptive:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " The embedding for position 5 can encode whatever distributional pattern the training data associates with that position. In a corpus where sentence-initial positions carry different word distributions, the learned vectors reflect that."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "No inductive bias to undo:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " The model is free to represent position in any way that minimises the training loss. It is not constrained to represent relative offsets or smooth frequency patterns."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Empirically comparable:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Vaswani et al. (2017) reported nearly identical translation BLEU scores between learned and sinusoidal encodings on the same architecture. The choice of PE type rarely drives large accuracy differences in practice."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Extrapolation Problem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The most significant limitation is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "hard truncation at max_len"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". If a model is trained with max_len = 512 and given a sequence of 600 tokens at inference time, positions 512–599 have no corresponding embedding — the lookup would index out of bounds. The only solutions are:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Truncate the input to max_len (loses information)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Fine-tune with a larger max_len, extending the embedding table."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Switch to a relative or RoPE encoding that is not length-bounded."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\nmax_len = 512\nd_model = 768\n\npos_emb = nn.Embedding(max_len, d_model)\n\n# Works fine:\npositions_ok = torch.arange(512)   # indices 0..511\nprint(pos_emb(positions_ok).shape)  # (512, 768)\n\n# Fails at runtime:\ntry:\n    positions_bad = torch.arange(600)  # 512 and beyond don't exist\n    pos_emb(positions_bad)\nexcept IndexError as e:\n    print(f\"Error: {e}\")\n# IndexError: index out of range in self — or silent garbage depending on PyTorch version"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Extending to Longer Sequences (Fine-tuning)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nfrom transformers import BertConfig, BertModel\n\n# Load BERT with max_len=512\nmodel = BertModel.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')\nold_pe = model.embeddings.position_embeddings.weight  # (512, 768)\n\n# Extend to 1024 by copying the original weights and zero-initialising the rest\nnew_max_len = 1024\nnew_pe = nn.Embedding(new_max_len, 768)\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    new_pe.weight[:512] = old_pe          # copy original 512 positions\n    # positions 512..1023 start at zero; fine-tuning on longer texts will fill them in\n\nmodel.embeddings.position_embeddings = new_pe\nmodel.config.max_position_embeddings = new_max_len\n\n# Now fine-tune on data with sequences up to 1024 tokens..."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to Use Learned vs Sinusoidal"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For most applications, the choice does not significantly affect downstream task performance. The practical decision factors are:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Use learned"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " when the application has a known, fixed maximum length (e.g., document classification up to 512 tokens) and you want the model to adapt its position representations."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Use sinusoidal"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " when sequence lengths are unpredictable or may exceed training lengths at inference."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Prefer RoPE or ALiBi"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " (see next subtopics) for modern LLMs that need to handle variable-length contexts efficiently and extrapolate to long sequences."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Key insight:"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " Learned positional embeddings are exactly as flexible as token embeddings — they can represent any pattern the training data supports. Their Achilles heel is that they are a finite lookup table: position 513 simply does not exist if max_len = 512. This is why modern LLMs increasingly use relative position encodings (RoPE, ALiBi) that compute position on-the-fly and generalize to any length."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
